## 🐛 Bug Report

<!-- A clear and concise description of what the bug is. -->

When trying to write a large workbook (10 by 500,000) into a buffer, Node ran out-of-memory. The resulting file should be at most of 15Mo which seems reasonable from a memory stand-point.

The code below is a reproduction case for a case I got on an application running in the browser and performing `writeBuffer` on a 7 by 220k grid full of data and with formatting on each cell.

Lib version: 4.4.0

## Steps To Reproduce

<!-- The exact steps required to reproduce the issue, ideally with a code example -->

```javascript
import pkg from "exceljs";
const { Workbook } = pkg;

const workbook = new Workbook();
const worksheet = workbook.addWorksheet(undefined, {
  views: [{ showGridLines: true }],
});
for (let columnIndex = 0; columnIndex !== 10; ++columnIndex) {
  for (let rowIndex = 0; rowIndex !== 500_000; ++rowIndex) {
    const cell = worksheet.getCell(rowIndex + 1, columnIndex + 1);
    cell.value = "Xxx Xxxxxx Xxx Xxxxxx Xxxxxxxxxxxx";
    const defaultBorder = {
      style: "thin",
      color: { argb: "E0E0E0" },
    };
    cell.style = {
      border: {
        bottom: defaultBorder,
        left: defaultBorder,
        right: defaultBorder,
        top: defaultBorder,
      },
      vertical: "middle",
    };
  }
}
await workbook.xlsx.writeBuffer({ useStyles: true });
// await workbook.xlsx.write('filename.xlsx', { useStyles: true }); // does not work either
```

## The expected behaviour:

<!-- A clear and concise description of what you expected to happen. -->

Given 100,000 rows results into a 2,287 Ko file, I don't expect 500,000 rows to cause out-of-memory of Node when creating the file.

The code above fails with:

```
FATAL ERROR: Reached heap limit Allocation failed - JavaScript heap out of memory
```

## Possible solution (optional, but very helpful):

None yet. Except maybe dropping all the styling, but not an ideal option given I want to preserve it.

