By reading the documentation, I fell upon an helper called `Excel.stream.xlsx.WorkbookWriter`. Unfortunately it cannot make it in my case as I'm on a browser so I cannot really trigger filesystem APIs.

But what's interesting is that when switching to it, I don't have the OOM anymore if I go for a file export.

<details>
<summary>Snippet</summary>

```js
const workbook = new Excel.stream.xlsx.WorkbookWriter({
  filename: "streamed.xlsx",
  useStyles: true,
});
const worksheet = workbook.addWorksheet(undefined, {
  views: [{ showGridLines: true }],
});
for (let rowIndex = 0; rowIndex !== 500_000; ++rowIndex) {
  for (let columnIndex = 0; columnIndex !== 10; ++columnIndex) {
    const cell = worksheet.getCell(rowIndex + 1, columnIndex + 1);
    cell.value = "Xxx Xxxxxx Xxx Xxxxxx Xxxxxxxxxxxx";
    const defaultBorder = {
      style: "thin",
      color: { argb: "E0E0E0" },
    };
    cell.style = {
      border: {
        bottom: defaultBorder,
        left: defaultBorder,
        right: defaultBorder,
        top: defaultBorder,
      },
      vertical: "middle",
    };
  }
  worksheet.getRow(rowIndex + 1).commit();
}
worksheet.commit();
await workbook.commit();
```
</details>

But this solution made me thing of a possible trick to make it work in the browser. As the library relies on stream and fs being two node only library I tweaked the library to import `@zenfs/core` instead of fs and everything could work via a fake file system replacing fs.

The only requirement would be to have "Excel.stream" accessible from the browser.
